&gt; How can I concatenate these strings while keeping null terminators in the middle of the resulting string? 

Not possible to form a C _string_ with anything after the _null character_.  The _string_ ends at `&#39;\0&#39;`.

Instead, write 15*4 bytes using `fwrite()`

    void printHeader(char *Category_Names) {
      //  printf(&quot;%s %s %s %s&quot;, Category_Names,(char*)Category_Names+15, ...
      fwrite(Category_Names, 15, 4, stdout);
    }

Recommend to open the file in binary too.


---

Yet consider another approach if the 4 strings lack spaces, pad output with spaces. IMO, padding with _null character&#39;s_ is not likely the approach to use.


    printf(&quot;%14s %14s %14s %14s\n&quot;, 
      Category_Names, Category_Names+15,
      Category_Names+30, Category_Names+45);

&gt; Quizzes\0\0\0\0\0\0\0\0Midterms...

Usually, the semantics of `strncat` render it fairly confusing, but this is exactly what it was designed to do; possible [history][1]. The are four `&#39;\0&#39;`&#39;s that are actually not needed in this case except for convenience when extracting the strings, so one also has to set these. It is probably easier to do `struct { char s0[15], s1[15], s2[15], s3[15]; };`, but maybe your professor wouldn&#39;t like that.

    #include &lt;stdio.h&gt;  /* printf */
    #include &lt;string.h&gt; /* strncpy */
    
    #define LEN 14
    
    static char *str15cpy(char *const s1, const char *const s2) {
    	char *const ret = strncpy(s1, s2, LEN);
    	s1[LEN] = &#39;\0&#39;;
    	return ret;
    }
    
    int main(void) {
    	char multistr[(LEN + 1) * 4];
    	char *s0 = multistr, *s1 = multistr + LEN + 1,
    		*s2 = multistr + (LEN + 1) * 2, *s3 = multistr + (LEN + 1) * 3;
    	size_t i;
    	str15cpy(s0, &quot;quizzes&quot;);
    	str15cpy(s1, &quot;midterms&quot;);
    	str15cpy(s2, &quot;homework&quot;);
    	str15cpy(s3, &quot;final&quot;);
    	/* This is what it looks like in memory. */
    	for(i = 0; i &lt; 60; i++)
    		{ const char a = multistr[i]; printf(&quot;%c&quot;, a ? a : &#39;0&#39;); }
    	fputc(&#39;\n&#39;, stdout);
    	/* Since the strings are &#39;\0&#39; terminated (convenient) already, you can, */
    	printf(&quot;%s\t%s\t%s\t%s\n&quot;, s0, s1, s2, s3);
    	return 0;
    }

And use binary I/O with fixed length records.

